<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-08T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-08T18:00:00-05:00" n="409" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d409">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 659.119/352</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-08T19:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 8, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>114. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from War Trade Board]:</p>
                            <p>No. 798. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_TAE1">Taylor</persName>. Your 916, Embassy’s 10964, June 29, 6 p.m.
                                We believe you should make it clear to Seydoux and <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName> that if
                                Denmark assents to our tonnage proposal, good faith will oblige us
                                to make agreement unless fault can be fairly found with some other
                                demand they make, either upon rations or blockade, and this latter
                                does not seem probable as substantially all blockade measures now
                                agreed to and rations only are under discussion. Danes here expect
                                to receive reply respecting tonnage Monday next. Upon what do the
                                English and French base their belief that there is no probability of
                                Danish ships being withdrawn from present trip charters if general
                                agreement fails?</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>